{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621500"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16746"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16746"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.46,0.29,0,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9437"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52225"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7168"},{"type":"tags","id":"7242"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22312"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vertebral levels marks the typical termination of the spinal cord in adults?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T11","L1/L2","L3/L4","T12","L5/S1"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomy of the spinal cord termination is crucial for differentiating between spinal cord and nerve root injuries. The spinal cord typically terminates at the \u003Cstrong\u003EL1/L2\u003C/strong\u003E vertebral level in adults, forming the conus medullaris. Below this level, the spinal canal contains the cauda equina - a bundle of nerve roots resembling a horse\u0027s tail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET11 and T12 Levels\u003C/strong\u003E: Both T11 and T12 are above the typical termination point of the spinal cord. At these levels, the spinal cord proper is still present, containing grey and white matter. Injuries at these levels would directly impact the spinal cord itself rather than the cauda equina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL3/L4 and L5/S1 Levels\u003C/strong\u003E: These levels lie below the termination of the spinal cord at the conus medullaris. They contain only the nerve roots of the cauda equina. Injuries here affect the nerve roots and do not involve the spinal cord proper. L5/S1 is especially relevant in disc herniations but does not involve spinal cord injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical knowledge is clinically significant because injuries below L1/L2 typically have a better prognosis as they affect nerve roots (which have some regenerative capacity) rather than the spinal cord itself. Additionally, the pattern of neurological deficits differs between spinal cord and cauda equina injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cauda equina syndrome involves nerve roots below the L1/L2 level where the spinal cord terminates.","The conus medullaris typically ends at the L1/L2 vertebral level in adults.","Injuries below L1/L2 affect nerve roots rather than the spinal cord itself."],"references":["Deuchars SA, Lall VK. Sympathetic preganglionic neurons: properties and inputs. Compr Physiol. 2015 Apr;5(2):829-69. doi: 10.1002/cphy.c140020. PMID: 25880515","Gibbins I. Functional organization of autonomic neural pathways. Organogenesis. 2013 Jul-Sep;9(3):169-75. doi: 10.4161/org.25126. Epub 2013 Jun 6. PMID: 23872517; PMCID: PMC3896588","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Harrow-Mortelliti M, Reddy V, Jimsheleishvili G. Physiology, Spinal Cord. [Updated 2023 Mar 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544267/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16746"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52225"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T08:59:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T09:00:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9437"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"t